doc.after: Forms of Christianity have dominated religious life in what is now the United Kingdom for over 1,400 years.[337] Although a majority of citizens still identify with Christianity in many surveys, regular church attendance has fallen dramatically since the middle of the 20th century,[338] while immigration and demographic change have contributed to the growth of other faiths, most notably Islam.[339] This has led some commentators to variously describe the UK as a multi-faith,[340] secularised,[341] or post-Christian society.[342]
